{{head|hu|suffix}}

# {{lb|hu|case suffix}} [[until]], [[till]], [[up to]]. {{n-g|Used to form the [[terminative]] case. It can refer to both time and place. It is used by both back and front vowel words.}}
#: {{uxi|hu|√ñt'''ig''' dolgozom.|I work '''until''' five o'clock.}}
#: {{uxi|hu|Az √°llom√°s'''ig''' busszal ment√ºnk, de onnan haz√°'''ig''' m√°r [[gyalog]].|We traveled by bus '''to''' the station but from there '''to''' home we walked.}}
# [[for]] a specified length of time
#: {{uxi|hu|A lev√©l olyan hossz√∫ volt, hogy t√≠z perc'''ig''' olvastam.|The letter was so long that I was reading it '''for''' 10 minutes.}}

====Usage notes====
{{U:hu:case-endings}}
* The above two senses may be ambiguous when {{m|hu|√≥ra|hour ''or'' o'clock}} is mentioned, as in this sentence:
*: {{uxi|hu|K√©t √≥r√°'''ig''' maradunk.|We'll stay '''for''' two hours '''OR''' We'll stay '''until''' 2 o'clock.}}
: To avoid this ambiguity, the accusative case may be employed when referring to the duration ''(K√©t √≥r√°'''{{l|hu|-t|t}}''' maradunk),'' and the sentence may be rephrased when referring to the end point (''K√©t √≥ra {{m|hu|m√∫lva}} indulunk'' ‚Äì We're leaving '''in''' two hours.)
* {{sense|until}} With [[pointlike]] events or places the meaning is usually clear. However, it is ambiguous when the given event itself lasts for some time or the given object is such that it matters whether it is included, excluded or partially included.
*: {{uxi|hu|Szerd√°'''ig''' van id≈ëd.|You have time '''until''' Wednesday.}}
*:* With exclusion: on Wednesday 00:01 A.M. you are already late (rare, one would probably say ''keddig''; until Tuesday)
*:* With partial inclusion: the border line is somewhere during the day (most likely)
*:* With full inclusion: you have the full Wednesday (also possible)

===See also===
* {{l|hu|addig}}, {{l|hu|eddig}}, {{l|hu|meddig}}
