===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*-kos}}
From {{inh|en|enm|-ik}}, from {{der|en|fro|-ique}}, from {{der|en|la|-icus}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|[[*-kos|*-kos, *-·∏±os]]}}, formed with the [[Appendix:Glossary#i-stem|i-stem]] suffix {{m|ine-pro|*-i-}} and the adjectival suffix {{m|ine-pro|[[*-kos|*-kos, *-·∏±os]]}}. Compare {{cog|grc|-ŒπŒ∫œåœÇ}}, {{cog|sa|-‡§á‡§ï}} and {{cog|cu|-—ä–∫—ä}}. {{doublet|en|-y}}.

PIE {{m|ine-pro|*-kos}} on noun stems carried the meaning 'characteristic of, like, typical, pertaining to', and on adjectival stems it acted emphatically.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|en|/…™k/}}

===Suffix===
{{en-suffix|cat2=adjective-forming suffixes|cat3=productive suffixes}}

# {{n-g|Used to form adjectives from nouns with the meaning ‚Äúof or pertaining to‚Äù.}}
#: {{m|en|Cyrillic}}
#: {{m|en|acidic}}
# {{lb|en|chemistry}} {{n-g|Used to denote certain [[chemical compound]]s in which a specified [[chemical element]] has a higher [[oxidation number]] than in the equivalent compound whose name ends in the suffix {{m|en|-ous}}. For example [[sulphuric acid]] ([[hydrogen|H]]‚ÇÇ[[sulfate|SO‚ÇÑ]]) has more oxygen atoms per molecule than [[sulphurous acid]] (H‚ÇÇ[[sulfite|SO‚ÇÉ]]).}}

====Usage notes====
The suffix {{m|en|-ic}} is often added to words of Greek or Latin origin, but may also be used with other words, and in some cases is even added (redundantly) to adjectives, as in {{m|en|veganic}} (from {{m|en|vegan}}).

