{{head|non|pronouns|cat2=clitics}} {{tlb|non|enclitic}}

# {{non-gloss definition|enclitic form of {{m|non|√æ√∫}}}}
#* Haralds saga hins h√°rfagra 41.
#*: N√∫ t√≥k'''tu''' sv√° vi√∞ sem v√°rr konungr vildi.
#* Lokasenna 24.
#*: En √æik s√≠√∞a k√≥√∞u / Samseyju √≠ / ok drap'''tu''' √° v√©tt sem v«´lur / vitka l√≠ki / f√≥r'''tu''' ver√æj√≥√∞ yfir / ok hug√∞a ek √æat args a√∞al
#: {{suffixusex|non|skalt|skaltu|altsuf=√æ√∫|t1=shalt|t2=shalt thou}}
#: {{suffixusex|non|l√°t|l√°ttu|altsuf=√æ√∫|t1=let (impr.)|t2=let (impr.)}}

====Usage notes====
For reasons related to syntax, as well as Old Norse often explicitly stating the subject of verbs in the imperative, the verb is often followed by the subject pronoun. For {{m|non|√æ√∫}}, this is when it may take on an enclitic form. This is not to say, however, that whenever ''√æ√∫'' comes after a verb, it will always take an enclitic form. It could well stay separate for the sake of emphasis.

Which one of the variants {{m|non|-du}}, {{m|non|-√∞u}} and {{m|non|-tu}} to use, is decided by the same rules that decide which dental suffix to take in the type 1 weak verbs. This form is used after hard consonants.

====Descendants====
This feature is also present in modern Icelandic verb conjugation, with its imperative forms with appended personal pronouns (though only in the second person).

