====Verb====
{{en-verb|loses|losing|lost}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[cause]] (something) to cease to be in one's [[possession]] or [[capability]] due to [[unfortunate]] or [[unknown]] [[circumstance]]s, [[event]]s or [[reason]]s.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1963|author={{w|Margery Allingham}}|title={{w|The China Governess}}| chapter=19|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2004261W| passage=Meanwhile Nanny Broome was recovering from her initial panic and seemed anxious to make up for any kudos she might have '''lost''', by exerting her personality to the utmost. She took the policeman's helmet and placed it on a chair, and unfolded his tunic to shake it and fold it up again for him.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=April 15, 2011|author=Saj Chowdhury|work=BBC Sport| title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/13009332.stm Norwich 2-1 Nott'm Forest]| passage=Forest, who '''lost''' striker Kris Boyd to injury seconds before half-time, produced little after the break, with a Tyson sliced shot from 12 yards their only opportunity of note.}}
#: {{ux|en|If you '''lose''' that ten-pound note, you'll be sorry.}}
#: {{ux|en|He '''lost''' his hearing in the explosion.}}
#: {{ux|en|She '''lost''' her position when the company was taken over.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To have (an [[organ]]) [[remove]]d from one's [[body]], especially by [[accident]].
##: {{ux|en|Johnny '''lost''' a tooth, but kept it for the tooth fairy.}}
##: {{ux|en|He '''lost''' his spleen in a car wreck.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[shed]] ([[weight]]).
##: {{ux|en|I‚Äôve '''lost''' five pounds this week.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To experience the [[death]] of (someone to whom one has an attachment, such as a [[relative]] or [[friend]]).
##: {{ux|en|She '''lost''' all her sons in the war.}}
# To wander from; to miss, so as not to be able to find; to go astray from.
#: {{ux|en|I '''lost''' my way in the forest.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Tempest|I|ii|passage=He hath '''lost''' his fellows.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[fail]] to [[win]] (a game, competition, trial, etc).
#: {{ux|en|We '''lost''' the football match.}}
#: {{ux|en|You just '''lost''' [[The Game]].}}
#* {{RQ:Dryden Cleomenes}}
#*: I fought the battle bravely which I '''lost''', / And lost it but to Macedonians.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To be [[unable]] to [[follow]] or [[trace]] (somebody or something) any longer.
#: {{ux|en|The policeman '''lost''' the robber he was chasing.}}
#: {{ux|en|Mission control '''lost''' the satellite as its signal died down.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause (somebody) to be [[unable]] to [[follow]] or [[trace]] one any longer.
#: {{ux|en|We managed to '''lose''' our pursuers in the forest.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[cease]] [[exhibit]]ing; to [[overcome]] (a behavior or emotion).
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ron Liebman|title=Death by Rodrigo|year=2007| location=New York| publisher=Simon & Schuster| isbn=9781416535270| page=134| pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=c779Cd1_hoEC&pg=PA134| passage=I can see Mickie getting hot, I'm about to grab his arm, hold him back, say, Whoa, whoa, Mick, not here, it ain't worth it what happened inside just now. But I don't need to because Mickie '''loses''' his anger, starts smiling at ponytail, then melodramatically starts looking around at the men and women on the street going in and out of the courthouse.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|title=Dancing in the Rain|author=Tracy Brooks| page=349| ISBN=1475944500| passage=Her attitude was so bad my mother wound up telling her, ‚ÄúYou know we really don't have to be standing here talking to you, so you can '''lose''' the attitude or you can leave.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|informal}} To [[shed]], [[remove]], [[discard]], or [[eliminate]].
#: {{ux|en|When we get into the building, please '''lose''' the hat.}}
#*: {{quote-book|en|year=1976|title=Sexual Astrology|author=Martine|passage=You can bet that the next woman who '''"loses"''' the top half of her bikini at the beach was born under the sign of Libra.}}
# Of a [[clock]], to [[run]] slower than expected.
#: {{ux|en|My watch '''loses''' five minutes a week.}}
#: {{ux|en|It's already 5:30? My watch must have '''lost''' a few minutes.}}
# {{lb|en|ditransitive}} To cause (someone) the [[loss]] of something; to [[deprive]] of.
#* '''1650''', {{w|Richard Baxter}}, ''The Saints' Everlasting Rest''
#*: O false heart! thou hadst almost betrayed me to eternal flames, and '''lost''' me this glory.
#* '''a. 1699''', {{w|Sir William Temple, 1st Baronet}}, ''On the Excesses of Grief''
#*: How should you go about to '''lose''' him a wife he loves with so much passion?
#* '''2002''', {{w|Colin Jones (historian)|Colin Jones}}, ''The Great Nation'', Penguin 2003, page 556:
#*: This '''lost''' Catholicism {{...}} any semblance of a claim to special status, and also highlighted the gains which other religious formations had derived from the Revolution.
# To fail to catch with the mind or senses; to miss.
#: ''I '''lost''' a part of what he said.''

