==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*d ∞eh‚ÇÅ-}}
From {{inh-lite|en|enm|don}}, from {{inh-lite|en|ang|don|d≈çn}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*d≈çn}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*d≈çnƒÖ}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*d ∞eh‚ÇÅ-||to put, place, do, make}}.

For senses 4 and 5, compare [[w:Old Norse|Old Norse]] ''[[duga#Old_Norse|duga]]'', whence [[w:Danish|Danish]] ''[[du#Danish|du]]''.

The past tense form is from {{inh-lite|en|enm|didde}}, {{m-lite|enm|dude}}, from {{inh-lite|en|ang|dyde}}, {{m|ang|*diede}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*ded«≠}}/{{m|gem-pro|*dedƒì}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*d ∞√©d ∞eh‚ÇÅti}}, an athematic e-reduplicated verb of the same root {{m|ine-pro|*d ∞eh‚ÇÅ-}}.

The obligatory, meaningless use of ''do'' in interrogative, negative, and‚Äîformerly‚Äîaffirmative sentences, which is unusual in Germanic languages, is thought by some linguists to be one of the {{w|Brittonicisms in English}}, calqued from [[Brythonic]].<ref>{{cite-journal|author=John McWhorter|title=What else happened to English? A brief for the Celtic hypothesis|journal=English language & linguistics|location=Cambridge|publisher=University Press|date=2009|volume=13|issue=2|pages=163-191}}</ref> It is first recorded in Middle English, where it may have marked the [[perfective]] aspect, though in some cases the meaning seems to be [[imperfective]]. In {{w|Early Modern English}}, any meaning in such contexts was lost, making it a dummy auxiliary, and soon thereafter its use became mandatory in most questions and negations.

Doublets include {{m|en|deed}}, {{m|en|deem}}, {{m|en|-dom}}, but not {{m|en|deal}}. 

Other cognates include, via Latin, {{cog|en|feast}}, {{m|en|festival}}, {{m|en|fair||celebration}}, via Greek, {{cog|en|theo-}}, {{m|en|theme}}, {{m|en|thesis}}, and {{cog|sa|‡§¶‡§ß‡§æ‡§§‡§ø||to put}}, {{m|sa|‡§ß‡§æ‡§§‡•É||creator}} and {{m|sa|‡§ß‡§æ‡§§‡•Å||layer, element, root}}. 

