===Etymology===
A regional form adopted into colloquial standard German. In western Germany from {{der|de|gmw-cfr|dat}}, from northern {{inh|de|gmh|dat}}, from northern {{inh|de|goh|that}}, {{m|goh|dat}}, an [[w:Old High German consonant shift|unshifted]] relict form possibly due to [[Frankish]] influence. In northern Germany from {{der|de|nds-de|dat}}, from {{der|de|gml|dat}}, from {{der|de|osx|that}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|de|/dat/}}
* {{a|Berlin-Brandenburg}} also {{IPA|de|/d…êt/|/d…ôt/}}
* {{audio|de|De-dat.ogg|Audio}}

===Article===
{{head|de|article}}

# {{lb|de|colloquial|regional|also|_|Ruhrdeutsch}} {{alternative form of|de|das}}
#: {{ux|de|Gibste mir ma‚Äô '''dat''' Wasser?|Could you pass me '''the''' water?}}

===Pronoun===
{{de-pron}}

# {{lb|de|colloquial|regional}} {{alternative form of|de|das}}
#: {{ux|de|'''Dat''' wei√ü ich nich'.|I don't know '''that'''.}}

===Pronoun===
{{head|de|pronoun|cat2=personal pronouns}}

# {{lb|de|colloquial|regional|neuter nominative}} [[it]]

===Conjunction===
{{head|de|conjunction}}

# {{lb|de|colloquial|regional}} {{alternative form of|de|dass}}
#: {{ux|de|Ich glaub, '''dat''' der 'n bisschen √ºbertreibt.|I believe '''that''' he's exaggerating a little.}}

====Usage notes====
* Although found in the native dialects throughout northern and western Germany, the near-exclusive use of ''dat'' in colloquial standard German is most typical of the West (chiefly [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] and [[Rhineland-Palatinate]]). In the other areas the forms ''dat'' and ''das'' are used in free variation. In Berlin, the form {{m|de|dit}} (local form of {{l|de|dies|this}}) often has replaced ''dat''.

===References===
* http://www.atlas-alltagssprache.de/runde-1/f17a-c/

