===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*d ∞rewg ∞-|id=deceive}}
From {{inh|en|enm|drem}}, from {{inh|en|ang|drƒìam|t=music, joy}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*draum}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*draumaz}}, from earlier {{m|gem-pro|*draugmaz}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*d ∞rowg ∞-mos}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*d ∞rewg ∞-|t=to deceive, injure, damage}}. 

The sense of "dream", though not attested in Old English, may still have been present (compare {{cog|osx|dr≈çm|t=bustle, revelry, jubilation", also "dream}}), and was undoubtedly reinforced later in Middle English by {{cog|non|draumr|t=dream}}, from same Proto-Germanic root. 

Cognate with {{cog|sco|dreme||dream}}, {{cog|frr|drom||dream}}, {{cog|fy|dream||dream}}, {{cog|nds|Droom}}, {{cog|nl|droom||dream}}, {{cog|de|Traum||dream}}, {{cog|da|-}} and {{cog|nb|dr√∏m}}, {{cog|nn|draum}}, {{cog|sv|dr√∂m||dream}}, {{cog|is|draumur||dream}}. Related also to {{cog|ang|drƒìag||spectre, apparition}}, {{cog|nl|bedrog||deception, deceit}}, {{cog|de|Trug||deception, illusion}}.

{{rel-top|more details}}
The derivation from Old English ''drƒìam'' is controversial, since the word itself is only attested in writing in its meaning of ‚Äújoy, mirth, musical sound‚Äù. Possibly there was a separate word ''drƒìam'' meaning ‚Äúimages seen while sleeping‚Äù, which was avoided in literature due to potential confusion with the ‚Äújoy‚Äù sense. Otherwise, the modern sense must have been borrowed from another Germanic language, most probably Old Norse.<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}.</ref> Since this is the common sense in all Germanic languages outside the British isles, a spontaneous development from ‚Äújoy, mirth‚Äù to ‚Äúdream‚Äù in Middle English is hardly conceivable. In {{m+|osx|-}}, the cognate {{m|osx|dr≈çm}} did mean ‚Äúdream‚Äù, but was a rare word.

Attested words for ‚Äúsleeping vision‚Äù in Old English were {{m|ang|m«£ting}} (Middle English {{m|enm|m√¶te}}, {{m|enm|mete}}), from an unclear source, and {{m|ang|swefn}} (Modern {{cog|en|sweven}}), from {{cog|gem-pro|*swefnaz}}, from Proto-Indo-European {{m|ine-pro|*swepno-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*swep-}}; compare {{cog|grc|·ΩïœÄŒΩŒøœÇ||sleep}}.

The verb is from {{inh|en|enm|dremen}}, possibly (see above) from {{inh|en|ang|drƒ´eman||to make a joyous sound with voice or with instrument; rejoice; sing a song; play on an instrument}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*draumijanƒÖ}}, {{m|gem-pro|*draugmijanƒÖ||to be festive, dream, hallucinate}}, from the noun. Cognate with {{cog|sco|dreme||to dream}}, {{cog|fy|dreame||to dream}}, {{cog|nl|dromen||to dream}}, {{cog|de|tr√§umen||to dream}}, {{cog|sv|dr√∂mma||to dream, muse}}, {{cog|is|dreyma||to dream}}.
