===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*leyp-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|leven}}, from {{inh|en|ang|l«£fan|t=to leave}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*laibijan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*laibijanƒÖ|t=to let stay, leave}}, causative of {{m|gem-pro|*lƒ´banƒÖ|t=to stay, remain}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*leyp-|t=to stick; fat}}. 

Cognate with {{cog|ofs|lƒìva|t=to leave}}, {{cog|osx|lƒìvian}}, {{cog|goh|leiban|t=to leave}}, {{cog|non|leifa|t=to leave over}} (whence {{cog|is|leifa|t=to leave food uneaten}}), {{m|is|lifna|t=to be left}} (whence {{cog|da|levne}}). More at [[lave#Etymology_2|lave]], [[belive#Etymology_1|belive]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb|leaves|leaving|left}}

# To have a consequence or remnant.
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause or allow (something) to [[remain]] as [[available]]; to [[refrain]] from taking (something) away; to stop short of consuming or otherwise depleting (something) entirely.
##: {{ux|en|I '''left''' my car at home and took a bus to work.}}
##: {{ux|en|The ants did not '''leave''' so much as a crumb of bread.}}
##: {{ux|en|There's not much food '''left'''. We'd better go to the shops.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=7
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=[‚Ä¶] St.‚ÄâBede's at this period of its history was perhaps the poorest and most miserable parish in the East End of London. Close-packed, crushed by the buttressed height of the railway viaduct, rendered airless by huge walls of factories, it at once banished lively interest from a stranger's mind and '''left''' only a dull oppression of the spirit.}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|year=2013|month=May-June|author=[http://www.americanscientist.org/authors/detail/david-van-tassel David Van Tassel], [http://www.americanscientist.org/authors/detail/lee-dehaan Lee DeHaan]
|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2013/3/wild-plants-to-the-rescue Wild Plants to the Rescue]
|volume=101|issue=3|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}
|passage=Plant breeding is always a numbers game.{{nb...}}. The wild species we use are rich in genetic variation,{{nb...}}. In addition, we are looking for rare alleles, so the more plants we try, the better. These rarities may be new mutations, or they can be existing ones that are neutral‚Äîor are even selected against‚Äîin a wild population. A good example is mutations that disrupt seed dispersal, '''leaving''' the seeds on the heads long after they are ripe.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive|or|intransitive|copulative}} To cause, to result in.
##: {{ux|en|The lightning '''left''' her dazzled for several minutes.}}
##: {{ux|en|Infantile paralysis '''left''' him lame for the rest of his life.}}
##: {{ux|en|She '''left''' disappointed.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1899|author={{w|Stephen Crane}}
|title=[[s:Twelve O'Clock|Twelve O'Clock]]|chapter=1
|passage=There was some laughter, and Roddle was '''left''' free to expand his ideas on the periodic visits of cowboys to the town. ‚ÄúMason Rickets, he had ten big punkins a-sittin' in front of his store, an' them fellers from the Upside-down-F ranch shot 'em up{{nb...}}.‚Äù}}
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=23
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=The slightest effort made the patient cough. He would stand leaning on a stick and holding a hand to his side, and when the paroxysm had passed it '''left''' him shaking.}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-07-20|volume=408| issue=8845| magazine={{w|The Economist}}| title=[http://www.economist.com/news/http://www.economist.com/news/asia/21582043-villagers-enjoy-sunlight-after-dark-out-gloom Out of the gloom]| passage=[Rural solar plant] schemes are of little help to industry or other heavy users of electricity. Nor is solar power yet as cheap as the grid. For all that, the rapid arrival of electric light to Indian villages is long overdue. When the national grid suffers its next huge outage, as it did in July 2012 when hundreds of millions were '''left''' in the dark, look for specks of light in the villages.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To put; to place; to deposit; to deliver, with a sense of withdrawing oneself.
##: {{ux|en|'''Leave''' your hat in the hall.}}
##: {{ux|en|We should '''leave''' the legal matters to lawyers.}}
##: {{ux|en|I '''left''' my sewing and went to the window to watch the falling snow.}}
##* {{RQ:KJV|Matthew|5|24|passage='''Leave''' there thy gift before the altar and go thy way.}}
##* {{RQ:Shakespeare King John|IV|iii|passage=The foot / That '''leaves''' the print of blood where'er it walks.}}
# To depart; to separate from.
## To [[let be]] or do without interference.
##: {{ux|en|I '''left''' him to his reflections.}}
##: {{ux|en|I '''leave''' my hearers to judge.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[depart]] from; to end one's connection or [[affiliation]] with.
##: {{ux|en|I '''left''' the country and I '''left''' my wife.}}
##* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=1|passage=I was about to say that I had known the Celebrity from the time he wore kilts. But I see I will have to amend that, because he was not a celebrity then, nor, indeed, did he achieve fame until some time after I '''left''' New York for the West.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[end]] one's [[membership]] in (a group); to terminate one's affiliation with (an organization); to [[stop]] participating in (a project).
##* '''2018''', ''The Independent'', "Brexit: Theresa May 'not bluffing' in threat to leave EU without a deal, Tory minister Liam Fox says"
##*: If we were to '''leave''', the economic impact on a number of European countries would be severe.
##: {{ux|en|I '''left''' the band.}}
## {{lb|en|intransitive}} To depart; to [[go away]] from a certain place or state.
##: {{ux|en|I think you'd better '''leave'''.}}
# To transfer something.
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[transfer]] [[possession]] of after death.
##: {{ux|en|When my father died, he '''left''' me the house.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[give]] (something) to someone; to [[deliver]] (something) to a repository; to [[deposit]].
##: {{ux|en|I'll '''leave''' the car in the station so you can pick it up there.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To transfer [[responsibility]] or [[attention]] of (something) (to someone); to [[stop]] being [[concerned]] with.
##: {{ux|en|Can't we just '''leave''' this to the experts?}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To [[remain]] (behind); to [[stay]].
#* {{RQ:Mlry MrtDrthr|20.11|2|XVIII|xj|passage=And whanne sire launcelot sawe them fare soo / he gat a spere in his hand / and there encountred with hym al attones syr bors sir Ector and sire Lyonel / and alle they thre smote hym atte ones with their speres /{{...}}/ and by mysfortune sir bors smote syre launcelot thurgh the shelde in to the syde / and the spere brake / and the hede '''lefte''' stylle in his syde}}
<!--Prior quote:And by myssefortune Sir Bors smote Sir Launcelot thorow the shylde into the syde, and the speare brake and the hede '''leffte''' stylle in the syde.-->
#* {{RQ:Hough Purchase Price|chapter=II|text=Carried somehow, somewhither, for some reason, on these surging floods, were these travelers,{{nb...}}. Even such a boat as the ''Mount Vernon'' offered a total deck space so cramped as to '''leave''' secrecy or privacy well out of the question, even had the motley and democratic assemblage of passengers been disposed to accord either.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To [[stop]], desist from; to "[[leave off]]" (+ noun / gerund).
#* '''1526''', {{w|William Tyndale}}, trans. ''Bible'', {{w|Gospel of Luke|Luke}} V:
#*: When he had '''leeft''' speakynge, he sayde vnto Simon: Cary vs into the depe, and lett slippe thy nette to make a draught.
#* '''1589''' or '''1590''', {{w|Christopher Marlowe}}, ''The Jew of Malta'', Act I.iv.21:
#*: I will learn to''' leave''' these fruitless tears ‚Ä¶
#* '''1716''' {{w|Lady Mary Wortley Montagu}}, ''The Basset-Table. An Eclogue.''[http://spenserians.cath.vt.edu/TextRecord.php?&action=GET&textsid=7867]
#*: Now '''leave''' Complaining, and begin your Tea.

